    <section class="mechanism">
      <h2>How Caffeine Works</h2>
      <p class="mechanism-intro">Caffeine is one of the most studied compounds in nutritional science. Four mechanisms explain how it works.</p>
      <div class="mechanism-card">
        <div class="mechanism-points">
          <div class="point"><h4><span class="point-num">1.</span>Blocks adenosine.</h4><p>Caffeine fits into adenosine receptors in the brain. Adenosine is the molecule that builds up through the day and signals tiredness. When caffeine blocks it, alertness comes through.</p></div>
          <div class="point"><h4><span class="point-num">2.</span>Supports dopamine signaling.</h4><p>Caffeine has been studied for its role in supporting healthy dopamine activity. Dopamine is the neurotransmitter behind motivation and focus.</p></div>
          <div class="point"><h4><span class="point-num">3.</span>Supports the release of catecholamines.</h4><p>Caffeine supports the release of norepinephrine and related molecules involved in alertness, attention, and physical energy.</p></div>
          <div class="point"><h4><span class="point-num">4.</span>Pairs naturally with L-theanine.</h4><p>Caffeine's effects are most studied when paired with L-theanine at a 2:1 ratio. Together, they support focus and energy without the overstimulation that can come with caffeine alone. More on this below.</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="mechanism-footnote">Summarized from published research on caffeine and cognitive performance.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="pairing">
      <p class="pairing-eyebrow">The Pairing</p>
      <h2>Caffeine + L-Theanine</h2>
      <div class="pairing-card">
        <div class="pairing-ratio">2 : 1</div>
        <p class="pairing-ratio-label">L-Theanine to Caffeine</p>
        <p>Caffeine on its own produces alertness, but at higher doses it can produce jitters and a crash. L-theanine is an amino acid studied for promoting alpha brain wave activity, the calm-focused state.</p>
        <p>Paired at a 2:1 ratio (L-theanine to caffeine), the combination has been studied for faster reaction times, better attention accuracy, and fewer of the over-stimulation effects caffeine can cause alone.</p>
        <p>DayShift uses exactly that ratio: <strong>120 mg of caffeine, 240 mg of L-theanine</strong>, every packet.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

